# Verify the `Z` chord's asymmetric semantics in the cheatsheet.
#
# Spec (per CLAUDE.md & code reading):
#   - Press Z when nothing is collapsed → collapse_all().
#   - Press Z when ≥1 section is collapsed → expand_all().
#
# Edge case (the actual bug): if the user collapses ONE section with
# `z`, then presses `Z`, the code branch `if c.collapsed.is_empty()`
# is FALSE, so `Z` does `expand_all()` — wiping the user's single
# collapse instead of collapsing the rest. This .test reproduces.

write hello.rs "fn main() {}"
open hello.rs

command view.cheatsheet
expect screen contains "Cheatsheet"

# Step 1: collapse ONE section with `z`.
key z
expect screen contains "(collapsed)"

# Step 2: press `Z` — naively the user expects collapse-all, but the
# code branches on `collapsed.is_empty()`, so it triggers expand_all.
# After Z, NO section should still be collapsed.
key Z
expect screen lacks "(collapsed)"
